# Collaboration and Communication Rules

## Ask Before Assuming

If requirements conflict, are ambiguous, or a key detail is missing, ask a clarification question **before** writing any code.

> Example triggers:
> - "Should this endpoint be authenticated?"
> - "Is the rule evaluation synchronous or via a queue?"
> - "Should deleting an employee also delete their sessions?"

Do not guess and implement — surface the ambiguity instead.

## Explain Non-Obvious Decisions

When a design decision isn't self-evident, add a brief comment or include a short explanation in your response.

```ts
// Using upsert here because the daily stats row may or may not exist
// depending on whether any event was ingested earlier today.
await this.prisma.dailyEmployeeStats.upsert({ ... });
```

Keep explanatory comments on the *why*, not the *what*. Do not narrate what the code already says.

## Preserve TODOs and FIXMEs

- Do not delete `TODO` or `FIXME` comments unless you have actually resolved the underlying issue.
- If you complete a TODO, remove the marker and briefly mention it in your response.

```ts
// ❌ BAD — silently removed a TODO without doing the work
// (no TODO here anymore, but auth was never added)

// ✅ GOOD — TODO stays until auth is implemented
// TODO: add JWT guard once AuthModule is wired up
@Get()
findAll() { ... }
```

## Keep Changes Commit-Sized

- One logical concern per change. Do not mix a refactor, a bug fix, and a new feature in the same response.
- If you notice an unrelated improvement while working, mention it instead of silently making the change.

> "I noticed the `SessionsService` has a similar pagination pattern that could be extracted — want me to do that separately?"
